  "prompt": "If light has no mass, how can a solar sail be propelled?",
  "response": "Although light has no mass, it does carry momentum. This is a key principle behind the operation of a solar sail, which is a method of spacecraft propulsion that uses the pressure exerted by sunlight.\n\nWhen light (photons) strikes a surface, it exerts a force on that surface due to its momentum. The momentum of light can be understood through the relationship:\n\n- \\( p = \\frac{E}{c} \\)\n\nwhere \\( p \\) is momentum, \\( E \\) is energy, and \\( c \\) is the speed of light. Photons carry momentum even though they are massless.\n\nWhen sunlight reflects off the solar sail, it transfers momentum to the sail. This transfer of momentum imparts a small force on the sail, which, although tiny, can accumulate over time to produce significant acceleration. The effectiveness of a solar sail depends on the total area of the sail and the intensity of the sunlight.\n\nTherefore, based on principles from physics, particularly conservation of momentum, solar sails can be propelled by harnessing the momentum carried by photons, allowing spacecraft to travel through space without the need for traditional fuel.",
